metadata.name: The Living Book #2 Moonrise #32
metadata.description:
I have been exploring the medium of print for years. Mixing etching, silk-screening, offset, photocopy, risography, drawing and painting to design and craft experimental art books.From the day digital, which had always fascinated me, took over my publishing practice, I always liked to create bridges between these two worlds.

The Living Books is part of this series of hybrid and experimental works where paper and digital resonate.

This issue #2 is made of 64 pages that will be minted by collectors. A book will eventually be printed and the pages will follow the mint order. Each page exists in a cover version (c) and a xerox version (x).

Controls :

• Click to dive into each frame.
• Press C to toggle cover mode.
• Press X to toggle xerox mode.
• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

The Living Book #2 Moonrise by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #29
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Lands of Solitude #14
metadata.description:
In times of chaos and uncertainty while the digital world falls appart, some will decide to resist and build. In their blind quest for curiosity, knowledge and creation, they will endure the darkest times and as waves of departures will follow one another, very few will remain. These are the lands of solitude that await.

Controls :
* Drag and pan to rotate and zoom.
* Press « F » to toggle the All-Over mode.
* Press « G » to toggle the grid.
* Press « H » to toggle the in-world infos.
* Press the space bar to toggle the auto scroll mode.
* Press « R » to restart.

———————

Lands of Solitude by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Foundations #246
metadata.description:
In march of this year, I started working on a new series involving multi-layering, and overriding shapes. Drawing and playing with colors and opacity.
It started with squares and grid, it then involved deformations, and circles and other experimentations.
This path fits with my artistic generative approach: rather than having a completely predefined idea, I start with a simple concept that evolves during creation. Then surprises happened, and I embraced them.

But this year was not like any other: 2022 has gifted me with a new birthday, the one of my son.

Over the past twelve months, I’ve watched him discovering the world surrounding him, learning and trying new things, laughing, or getting frustrated, sad or happy…
While learning to become a parent, I’ve been in an introspection phase where I questioned what it means to be “a father”. What impact will I have on my son, consciously or not?

“Foundations” takes shape in this context: 2 humans trying and exploring while being inspired by each other.
This series is a first of a set of at least 3, that illustrates an idea of what is an “Identity”, and what makes us who we are.

The foundations of an identity are laid in the first days of a child’s life. They will be influenced by many factors; including parenting, cultural environment, life experiences… 
Of course, as humans we are in constant evolution; life happens, sometimes for the best, sometimes for the worst, and our personality will be impacted…
But this will be a topic for another time. 


Today, we are at the start.

metadata.name: Mines #63
metadata.description:
"He found himself wondering at times, especially in the autumn, about the wild lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his dreams"
- J.R.R. Tolkien

Mines is an exploration of these mountains of dreams, and the ancient mechanics that shape them. The work of eons, where the landscapes we know rise and fall like ocean waves.

To know them, we must go beneath the mountain.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press “s” to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at specific width
- Use param ?bg=true to render on full color background (instead of the default dark background)

metadata.name: sketch: cairn() #12
metadata.description:
A cairn is a monument made of stacked rocks. In modern times, often used for wayfinding in remote areas, as in mountaineering, or to indicate an area of significance.

In this sketch I imagine these monuments -- through the looking glass. Paying mind to the simplicity of their construction, as well as the mysticism of what each might represent.

---

Sketch is a series meant to celebrate learning and experimentation.

In this sketch I experiment with subdivision, smoothing, textures, multiple levels of domain warping, and illustration techniques.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press s to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at size

metadata.name: White Mountain Winter #107
metadata.description:
White Mountain Winter is collaboration between myself and the machine to describe scenes that are real, or were. Yet perhaps now foreign, or out of time, or far away. I provide the seed of a dream I remember, and trust the machine to help make it real again.

I grew up in a town much like some of these, homes dispersed throughout the valley beneath the shadows of the mountains rising around. This is a tribute to the memory of wintertime in that place; bleak, cold, grey, with the light seemingly always fading. Yet at the same time, the feeling of calm, solace, peace resonating through. Exposed to the mountain elements, yet protected by them. A delicate arrangement, but essential.

The seed of magic I remember is present in the experience of falling snow at dusk. Large flakes tumbling down and blanketing everything, no end in sight. The most striking thing is the silence. The fallen snow absorbing all distraction, insisting that your focus be sharpened to a singularity; right there, right then.

---
- Best rendered in Chrome browser (best performance, & canvas blur - please be patient :)
- Made with p5js
- Press "s" to save png

metadata.name: Inland Emotions #40
metadata.description:
Inland Emotions

Over the centuries, ancient philosophers and modern psychologists have come to the same basic conclusion. The fact is that, according to a few millennia of research, there are a limited number of distinct human emotions, predefined by the human psyche. Sometimes it may seem like we are experiencing a "new" one, but on closer inspection, we see that it is the known emotions that are superimposed. Emotions are what they are, and they exist in the same way in each of us, whether we recognize them for what they are or not. But as our history blends into a new emerging state of the world, a whole new range of emotional responses are triggered within us. An infinite maelstrom of variations generated from a simple combination of a few emotions.
